{"nodes":[{"pos":[12,60],"content":"Working with Project Properties | Microsoft Docs","needQuote":false,"needEscape":true,"nodes":[{"content":"Working with Project Properties | Microsoft Docs","pos":[0,48]}]},{"content":"Working with Project Properties","pos":[725,756]},{"content":"In the IDE, all information that is needed to build a project is exposed as              <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>properties<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[757,859],"source":"In the IDE, all information that is needed to build a project is exposed as              *properties*."},{"content":"This information includes the application name, extension (such as DLL, LIB, EXE), compiler options, linker options, debugger settings, custom build steps, and many other things.","pos":[860,1038]},{"content":"You use              <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>property pages<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> (             <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Project &amp;#124; Properties<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>) to view and modify these properties.","pos":[1039,1158],"source":" You use              *property pages* (             **Project &#124; Properties**) to view and modify these properties."},{"content":"When you create a project, the system assigns values for various properties.","pos":[1165,1241]},{"content":"The defaults vary somewhat depending on the kind of project and what options you choose in the app wizard.","pos":[1242,1348]},{"content":"For example, an ATL project has properties related to MIDL files, but these are absent in a basic console application.","pos":[1349,1467]},{"content":"The default properties are shown in the General pane in the Property Pages:","pos":[1470,1545]},{"content":"Visual C&amp;#43;&amp;#43; Project Defaults","pos":[1554,1589],"source":"Visual C&#43;&#43; Project Defaults"},{"content":"Some properties, such as the application name, apply to all build variations, regardless of the target platform or whether it is a debug or release build.","pos":[1673,1827]},{"content":"But most properties are configuration-dependent.","pos":[1828,1876]},{"content":"This is because the compiler has to know what specific platform the program will run on and what specific compiler options to use in order to generate the correct code.","pos":[1879,2047]},{"content":"Therefore, when you set a property, it is important to pay attention to which configuration and platform the new value should apply to.","pos":[2048,2183]},{"content":"Should it apply only to Debug  Win32 builds, or should it also apply to Debug  ARM and Debug  x64?","pos":[2185,2283]},{"content":"For example, the              <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Optimization<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property, by default, is set to              <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Maximize Speed (/O2)<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> in a Release configuration, but is disabled in the Debug configuration.","pos":[2284,2472],"source":" For example, the              **Optimization** property, by default, is set to              **Maximize Speed (/O2)** in a Release configuration, but is disabled in the Debug configuration."},{"content":"The property pages are designed so that you can always see, and if necessary modify, which configuration and platform a property value should apply to.","pos":[2479,2630]},{"content":"The following illustration shows the property pages with the configuration and platform information in the list boxes at the top.","pos":[2631,2760]},{"content":"When the Optimization property is set here, it will apply only to Debug Win32 builds, which happens to be the active configuration, as shown by the red arrows.","pos":[2761,2920]},{"content":"Visual C&amp;#43;&amp;#43; Property Pages showing active configuration","pos":[2929,2991],"source":"Visual C&#43;&#43; Property Pages showing active configuration"},{"content":"The following illustration shows the same project property page, but the configuration has been changed to Release.","pos":[3129,3244]},{"content":"Note the different value for the Optimization property.","pos":[3245,3300]},{"content":"Also note that the active configuration is still Debug.","pos":[3301,3356]},{"content":"You can set properties for any configuration here; it doesn't have to be the active one.","pos":[3357,3445]},{"content":"Visual C&amp;#43;&amp;#43; Property Pages showing release config","pos":[3454,3510],"source":"Visual C&#43;&#43; Property Pages showing release config"},{"content":"The project system itself is based on MSBuild, which defines file formats and rules for building projects of any kind.","pos":[3636,3754]},{"content":"MSBuild manages much of the complexity of building for multiple configurations and platforms, but you need to understand a little bit about how it works.","pos":[3755,3908]},{"content":"This is especially important if you want to define custom configurations or create reusable sets of properties that you can share and import into multiple projects.","pos":[3909,4073]},{"content":"Project properties are stored either directly in the project file (*.vcxproj) or in other .xml or .props files that the project file imports and which supply default values.","pos":[4080,4253]},{"content":"As shown earlier, the same property for the same configuration may be assigned a different value in different files.","pos":[4254,4370]},{"content":"When you build a project, the MSBuild engine evaluates the project file and all the imported files in a well-defined order (described below).","pos":[4371,4512]},{"content":"As each file is evaluated, any property values defined in that file will override the existing values.","pos":[4513,4615]},{"content":"Any values that are not specified are inherited from files that were evaluated earlier.","pos":[4617,4704]},{"content":"Therefore, when you set a property with property pages, it is also important to pay attention to where you set it.","pos":[4706,4820]},{"content":"If you set a property to \"X\" in a .props file, but the property is set to \"Y\" in the project file, then the project will build with the property set to \"Y\".","pos":[4821,4977]},{"content":"If the same property is set to \"Z\" on a project item, such as a .cpp file, then the MSBuild engine will use the \"Z\" value.","pos":[4978,5100]},{"content":"For more information, see              <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Property inheritance<ept id=\"p1\">](#bkmkPropertyInheritance)</ept> later in this article.","pos":[5101,5211],"source":" For more information, see              [Property inheritance](#bkmkPropertyInheritance) later in this article."},{"content":"Build configurations","pos":[5220,5240]},{"content":"A configuration is just an arbitrary group of properties that are given a name.","pos":[5244,5323]},{"content":"Visual Studio provides Debug and Release configurations and each sets various properties appropriately for a debug build or release build.","pos":[5324,5462]},{"content":"You can use the                  <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Configuration Manager<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to define custom configurations as a convenient way to group properties for a specific flavor of build.","pos":[5463,5625],"source":" You can use the                  **Configuration Manager** to define custom configurations as a convenient way to group properties for a specific flavor of build."},{"content":"The Property Manager is used for advanced work with properties, but we introduce it here because it helps visualize property configurations.","pos":[5627,5767]},{"content":"You access it from                  <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>View &amp;#124;  Property Manager<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> or                  <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>View &amp;#124; Other Windows &amp;#124; Property Manager<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> depending on your settings.","pos":[5768,5939],"source":" You access it from                  **View &#124;  Property Manager** or                  **View &#124; Other Windows &#124; Property Manager** depending on your settings."},{"content":"It has nodes for each configuration/platform pair in the project.","pos":[5940,6005]}