ng illustration shows the Property Editor for the                  <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Additional Include Directories<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property after the                  <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Macros<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> button was chosen.","pos":[16905,17083],"source":" The following illustration shows the Property Editor for the                  **Additional Include Directories** property after the                  **Macros** button was chosen."},{"content":"When the                  <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Inherit from parent or project defaults<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> check box is selected and you add a new value, it is appended to any values that are currently being inherited.","pos":[17084,17265],"source":" When the                  **Inherit from parent or project defaults** check box is selected and you add a new value, it is appended to any values that are currently being inherited."},{"content":"If you clear the check box, your new value replaces the inherited values.","pos":[17266,17339]},{"content":"In most cases, leave the check box selected.","pos":[17340,17384]},{"content":"Property editor, Visual C&amp;#43;&amp;#43;","pos":[17393,17428],"source":"Property editor, Visual C&#43;&#43;"},{"pos":[17527,17568],"content":"Creating reusable property configurations"},{"content":"Although you can set \"global\" properties on a per-user, per-computer basis, we no longer recommend it.","pos":[17572,17674]},{"content":"Instead, we recommend that you use                  <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Property Manager<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to create a                  <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>property sheet<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> to store the settings for each kind of project that you want to be able to reuse or share with others.","pos":[17675,17896],"source":" Instead, we recommend that you use                  **Property Manager** to create a                  *property sheet* to store the settings for each kind of project that you want to be able to reuse or share with others."},{"content":"Property sheets also make it less likely that property settings for other project types will be inadvertently changed.","pos":[17897,18015]},{"content":"Property sheets are discussed in more detail                  <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Creating reusable property configurations<ept id=\"p1\">](#bkmkPropertySheets)</ept>.","pos":[18016,18143],"source":" Property sheets are discussed in more detail                  [Creating reusable property configurations](#bkmkPropertySheets)."},{"pos":[18151,18211],"content":"[!IMPORTANT]\n **.user files and why they are problematic**","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":".user files and why they are problematic","pos":[16,56]}]},{"content":"Past versions of Visual Studio used global property sheets that had a .user file name extension and were located in the <ph id=\"ph1\">\\&lt;</ph>userprofile&gt;\\AppData\\Local\\Microsoft\\MSBuild\\v4.0\\ folder.","pos":[18222,18402],"source":"Past versions of Visual Studio used global property sheets that had a .user file name extension and were located in the \\<userprofile>\\AppData\\Local\\Microsoft\\MSBuild\\v4.0\\ folder."},{"content":"We no longer recommend these files because they set properties for project configurations on a per-user, per-computer basis.","pos":[18403,18527]},{"content":"Such \"global\" settings can interfere with builds, especially when you are targeting more than one platform on your build computer.","pos":[18528,18658]},{"content":"For example, if you have both an MFC project and Windows Phone project, the .user properties would be invalid for one of them.","pos":[18659,18785]},{"content":"Reusable property sheets are more flexible and more robust.","pos":[18786,18845]},{"content":"Although .user files are still installed by Visual Studio and participate in property inheritance, they are empty by default.","pos":[18856,18981]},{"content":"The best practice is to delete the reference to them in                      <bpt id=\"p1\"